Martin Glinas IPA-fr elina; born June 5, 1970 is a Canadian former ice hockey forward who played List of NHL players with 1000 games played 1,273 games in the National Hockey League NHL for the Edmonton Oilers, Quebec Nordiques, Vancouver Canucks, Carolina Hurricanes, Calgary Flames, Florida Panthers and Nashville Predators.  A first round selection of the Los Angeles Kings, 7th overall, at the 1988 NHL Entry Draft, Glinas never played for the team as he was included in one of the most significant trades in NHL history while he was still playing junior hockey for the Gatineau Olympiques Hull Olympiques.  He was sent to the Oilers as a part of the Wayne Gretzky trade in 1988.
Glinas reached the Stanley Cup finals with four teams. He was a member of Edmonton's 1990 Stanley Cup Final 1990 championship team and also reached the final in 1994 Stanley Cup Final 1994 with Vancouver, 2002 Stanley Cup Final 2002 with Carolina and 2004 Stanley Cup Final 2004 with Calgary. He tied a record in the 2004 by scoring three series-winning goals in one playoff year.  After playing his final professional season with SC Bern in the Swiss National League A NLA, Glinas turned to coaching and plater development.  He is currently an assistant coach with the Calgary Flames
Playing career
Junior
Glinas played two seasons of junior hockey in the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League QMJHL for the Gatineau Olympiques Hull Olympiques between 1987 and 1989.  He scored 101 goal ice hockey goals and 107 assist ice hockey assists in 106 games.cite book  editor-last=Hanlon  editor-first=Peter  editor-last2=O'Brien  editor-first2=Sean  title=200304 Calgary Flames Media Guide  publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club  year=2003  pages=3839 In his first year, 198788 QMJHL season 198788, Glinas finished 10th in QMJHL scoring with 131 points.cite book  editor-last=Demers  editor-first=Denis  title=201314 QMJHL Media Guide  publisher=Quebec Major Junior Hockey League  year=2013  page=208 He won the Michel Bergeron Trophy as offensive rookie of the year and was named CHL Rookie of the Year Canadian Hockey League rookie of the year in addition to being named a QMJHL first-team all-star.cite web  url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=10526  title=Martin Gelinas biography  publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame  accessdate=2014-01-12 Glinas added 32 points in 17 playoff games as the Olympiques defeated the Drummondville Voltigeurs in the final to win the President's Cup QMJHL President's Cup.cite web  url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/player.htm?id=8447091  title=Martin Gelinas player card  publisher=National Hockey League  accessdate=2014-01-12  At the 1988 Memorial Cup, Glinas won the George Parsons Trophy as the most sportsmanlike player of the tournament.
The NHL Central Scouting Bureau National Hockey League NHL Central Scouting Bureau ranked Glinas as the eighth best prospect at the 1988 NHL Entry Draft.cite news  last=Grove  first=Bob  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2519&dat=19880610&id=AINdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K10NAAAAIBAJ&pg=5357,1929054  title=Quebec holds key to Pens' draft pick  work=The Observer-Reporter  location=Washington, PA  date=1988-06-10  accessdate=2014-01-12  page=B4 He was selected by the Los Angeles Kings with the seventh overall pick. Glinas never played for the Kings as on August 9, 1988, he was included in one of the most significant trades in NHL history.cite news  last=Gulitti  first=Tom  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=365&dat=19990225&id=dOcvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rD8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6718,3127013  title=Oilers miss Gretzky but move helped hockey  work=Cedartown Standard  date=1999-02-25  accessdate=2014-01-12  page=2B The Edmonton Oilers sent Wayne Gretzky, Mike Krushelnyski and Marty McSorley to the Kings in exchange for Gelinas, Jimmy Carson, three first round draft picks and $15 million in cash.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1842&dat=19880808&id=KsUhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=f50FAAAAIBAJ&pg=4669,1288387  title=Blockbuster trade sends The Great One to Kings  work=The Times Daily  location=Northwest Alabama  date=1988-08-10  accessdate=2014-01-12  page=B1 
As one of the key players coming to Edmonton in what he later called the biggest trade in sports history, Glinas endured the scrutiny of the Canadian media and pressure created by angry and disappointed fans after the Oilers dealt away a player in Gretzky who was considered a national icon.cite news  last=Pinchevsky  first=Tal  url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=679823  title=Gelinas, Carson were other pieces in Gretzky trade  publisher=National Hockey League  date=2013-08-09  accessdate=2014-01-31 Glinas began the 198889 NHL season 198889 season with the Oilers and made his NHL debut and scored his first point, on an assist, on October 7, 1988, against the New York Islanders. He scored his first goal ten days later against Jon Casey of the Minnesota North Stars but he was returned to Hull after six games to complete his second season of junior hockey.  Making his international debut, Glinas played with the Canada men's national junior ice hockey team Canadian national junior team at the 1989 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships.  He recorded two assists in seven games for the fourth place Canadians.cite web  url=http://www.tsn.ca/world_jrs/feature/?fid=3846  title=1989  Anchorage, USA  publisher=The Sports Network  accessdate=2014-01-12
Edmonton, Vancouver and Carolina
Joining the Oilers full-time in 198990 NHL season 198990, Glinas recorded 25 points in 46 games. At the age of 19, he was a member of Edmonton's Kid line ice hockey Line playing alongside 22-year-olds Joe Murphy ice hockey Joe Murphy and Adam Graves.  The trio provided an offensive boost in the post-season as the Oilers reached the 1990 Stanley Cup Final against the Boston Bruins.cite news  last=Nadel  first=Mike  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1914&dat=19900518&id=4IcgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LmUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4077,4411055  title='Kid Line' came to Oilers' rescue  work=Lewiston Sun-Journal  date=1990-05-18  accessdate=2014-01-12  page=37 Edmonton won the best-of-seven championship series four games to one and captured the Stanley Cup.cite magazine  last=Greenberg  first=Jay  url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1136800/1/index.htm  title=Still doing just great  work=Sports Illustrated  date=1990-06-04  accessdate=2014-01-12 After recording 40 points in 199091 NHL season 199091, Glinas scored only 29 points the 199192 NHL season following season. The Quebec Nordiques, who had been criticized by local fans and media for failing to select Glinas at the 1988 draft, attempted to acquire him in exchange for Bryan Fogarty.cite news  last=Dellapina  first=John  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-22608549.html  title=The urge to deal grows stronger  work=The Record  location=Bergen County, NJ  date=1991-12-29  accessdate=2014-01-12subscription required via=Highbeam The deal failed to materialize and Glinas remained with the Oilers for the 199293 NHL season 199293 season where his offensive production again declined, to 23 points.
The Nordiques finally acquired Glinas on June 20, 1993, in exchange for Scott Pearson.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19930621&id=yzAVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3AcEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4709,73342  title=Sports briefs  Hockey  work=Ocala Star-Banner  date=1993-06-21  accessdate=2014-01-12  page=2B He lasted only 31 games with Quebec before being placed on waivers NHL waivers and claimed by the Vancouver Canucks.cite book  last=Podnieks  first=Andrew  title=Players: The ultimate AZ guide of everyone who has ever played in the NHL  publisher=Doubleday Canada  year=2003  location=Toronto  page=283  isbn=0-385-25999-9 After scoring 16 points in 33 games to end the 199394 NHL season 199394 regular season with Vancouver, Glinas added nine points in 24 playoff games. The Canucks reached the 1994 Stanley Cup Final but were defeated in seven games by the New York Rangers.cite news  last=Barron  first=James  url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/18/nyregion/new-yorkers-bury-the-rangers-curse-in-a-sea-of-confetti.html  title=New Yorkers bury the Rangers' curse in a sea of confetti  work=New York Times  date=1994-06-18  accessdate=2014-01-12 In the 199495 NHL lockout lockout-shortened 199495 NHL season 199495 season, he scored 23 points in 46 games and won his first of two consecutive Fred J. Hume Awards as Vancouver's unsung hero.cite book  editor-last=Maniago  editor-first=Stephanie  editor-last2=Rollins  editor-first2=Jen  editor-last3=Brown  editor-first3=Ben  title=201314 Vancouver Canucks Media Guide  publisher=Vancouver Canucks Hockey Club  year=2013  pages=203204 Glinas finally achieved the offensive production expected of him when he was drafted by recording consecutive 30-goal seasons. He scored 30 goals in 199596 NHL season 199596 and led the Canucks with 35 goals, was second to Alexander Mogilny with 68 points and recorded a four-goal game against the Phoenix Coyotes in 199697 NHL season 199697.cite book  editor-last=Maniago  editor-first=Stephanie  editor-last2=Rollins  editor-first2=Jen  editor-last3=Brown  editor-first3=Ben  title=201314 Vancouver Canucks Media Guide  publisher=Vancouver Canucks Hockey Club  year=2013  pages=158, 193 He won three team awards: The Cyclone Taylor Award as Vancouver's most valuable player, the Molson Cup for earning the most three stars ice hockey three star selections and the Pavel Bure Most Exciting Player Award Most Exciting Player Award.
A collision with Edmonton's Dan McGillis early in the 199798 NHL season 199798 season forced Glinas out of the lineup with a sprained knee.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=19971014&id=Fl8vAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hdsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1412,3139877  title=Canucks blank Oilers but lose Gelinas to knee injury  work=Beaver country Times  date=1997-10-14  accessdate=2014-01-18  page=B5 He missed 16 games due to the injury and had only eight points in 24 games played. His tenure with the Canucks ended January 3, 1998. He was traded, along with Kirk McLean to the Carolina Hurricanes in exchange for Sean Burke, Geoff Sanderson and Enrico Ciccone.cite news  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-646635.html  title=Razing 'Canes in Carolina?  work=Washington Post  date=1998-01-04  accessdate=2014-01-18subscription required via=Highbeam Glinas was added to Carolina's roster to add a physical presence to the team and improve the team at both ends of the ice.cite news  last=Molinari  first=Dave  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19980112&id=MNJRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rm8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3567,2728388  title=Rugged Hurricanes have different look  work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette  date=1998-01-12  accessdate=2014-01-18  page=C5 He finished the season with 24 points in 40 games with the Hurricanes, and was invited to join Canada men's national ice hockey team Team Canada for the 1998 Men's World Ice Hockey Championships 1998 World Championship. Glinas scored one goal for the sixth-place Canadians.cite book  editor-last=Podnieks  editor-first=Andrew  title=IIHF Guide & Record Book 2012  year=2011  publisher=International Ice Hockey Federation  isbn=978-0-7710-9598-6  page=472
File:Gelinas-Conroy.png thumb left Gelinas left talks with former teammate Craig Conroy during the alumni game at the 2011 Heritage Classic.
Placed in a defensive role, Glinas's offensive statistics fell to 28 points in 199899 NHL season 199899 and 30 in 19992000 NHL season 19992000. The Hurricanes placed him on waivers NHL waivers late in the latter season, but remained with the team after he went unclaimed.cite news  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-432938.html  title=Gelinas, Hurricanes secure playoff spot  work=Washington Post  date=2001-04-07  accessdate=2014-01-18subscription required via=Highbeam His teammates expressed relief that he hadn't been moved the 200001 NHL season following season as, after improving to 59 points, Glinas scored the game-winning goal to clinch a playoff spot for Carolina. He recorded only one assist in six post-season games, then accepted a lessened role with the Hurricanes as he was placed on the third line in 200102 NHL season 200102.cite news  last=Peeler  first=Tim  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-12622970.html  title=Hurricane erases stormy memory  work=Roanoke Times  date=2002-05-30  accessdate=2014-01-18subscription required via=Highbeam  Glinas led the Hurricanes to their first Stanley Cup Final in franchise history after scoring the overtime-winning goal in the sixth game of the Eastern Conference NHL Eastern Conference final to eliminate the Toronto Maple Leafs.cite news  last=Wawrow  first=John  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1683&dat=20020529&id=3isqAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XUAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3831,7102262  title=Carolina puts away Toronto  work=Milwaukee Journal Sentinel  date=2002-05-29  accessdate=2014-01-18  page=2C Carolina fell to the Detroit Red Wings in five games in the 2002 Stanley Cup Final.cite news  url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=220613005  title=Red Wings achieve lofty Cup expectations  publisher=ESPN  date=2002-06-13  accessdate=2014-01-18
Calgary, Florida and Nashville
Glinas chose to decline his contract option for 200203 NHL season 200203 and left Carolina as a free agent.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1454&dat=20020626&id=9Q1PAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Vx8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3384,3089872  title=Hurricanes' Gelinas chooses free agency  work=Wilmington Morning Star  date=2002-06-26  accessdate=2014-01-18  page=5C He signed a contract with the Calgary Flames on July 2, 2002.cite news  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-54027328.html  title=Flames sign free agent F Gelinas  publisher=Associated Press  date=2002-07-02  accessdate=2014-01-18subscription required via=Highbeam A 52-point season was fourth best on the Flames and included his 500th career point, a game-winning goal against the Detroit Red Wings on January 25, 2003. Glinas reached another career milestone during the 200304 NHL season 200304 season as he played in his List of NHL players with 1000 games played 1,000th NHL game on December 9 against the Minnesota Wild.cite book  last=Podnieks  first=Andrew  title=The Flames: Celebrating Calgary's Dream Season, 200304  publisher=Fenn Publishing Company  year=2004  page=24 His 35 points on the season was again fourth-best on the team.cite book  last=Podnieks  first=Andrew  title=The Flames: Celebrating Calgary's Dream Season, 200304  publisher=Fenn Publishing Company  year=2004  page=54
In qualifying for the 2004 Stanley Cup Playoffs, the Flames reached the post-season for the first time in eight seasons.cite news  url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=240331003  title=Iginla's 40th goal ends long Calgary drought  publisher=ESPN  date=2004-03-31  accessdate=2014-01-20 With eight goals and 15 points in the playoffs, Glinas emerged as one of Calgary's post-season heroes.cite book  last=Podnieks  first=Andrew  title=The Flames: Celebrating Calgary's Dream Season, 200304  publisher=Fenn Publishing Company  year=2004  page=vii He scored the series-winning goal in overtime of game seven of the Flames' first round series against Vancouver. The victory advanced Calgary to the second round of the playoffs for the first time in 15 years.cite news  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23260032.html  title=NHL Report: Gelinas' goal carries Calgary to OT victory  work=The Columbian  location=Vancouver, WA  date=2004-04-20  accessdate=2014-01-20subscription required Glinas also scored the overtime goal that eliminated Detroit in six games,cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=20040504&id=bZpXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1vIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6917,4865735  title=Gelinas, Flames finish off Red Wings  work=Spokane Spokesman-Review  date=2004-05-04  accessdate=2014-01-20  page=C2 which made him the first player in NHL history to score three series-winning goals in overtime.cite news  last=Panaccio  first=Tim  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-118255225.html  title=Gelinas steps up to help Iginla  work=Philadelphia Inquirer  date=2004-05-26  accessdate=2014-01-20subscription required via=Highbeam He then became the second player in NHL history to score three series-clinching goals in one playoff year by tallying the goal that eliminated the San Jose Sharks and propelled the Flames into the 2004 Stanley Cup Final. His heroics throughout the post-season resulted in Glinas being called the Eliminator.
The Flames' Cinderella sports Cinderella run ended in the final as the Tampa Bay Lightning won the series in seven games.cite book  last=Podnieks  first=Andrew  title=The Flames: Celebrating Calgary's Dream Season, 200304  publisher=Fenn Publishing Company  year=2004  page=108 The result was controversial as Glinas appeared to have scored the tie-breaking goal in the sixth game that would have won the Stanley Cup for Calgary had the score held up.cite news  last=Snow  first=Chris  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-117869652.html  title=Controversy in Calgary: Lightning wins  work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune  date=2004-06-06  accessdate=2014-01-20subscription required via=Highbeam Television replays of the play showed that the puck deflected off Glinas' skate and appeared to be across the goal line before Tampa goaltender Nikolai Khabibulin kicked it out of the net. The referees did not signal a goal, however, and no video review was requested.  Tampa Bay went on to win the game in overtime.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=20040606&id=SbIyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0fIDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6800,3502038  title=Flames' Gelinas nearly won it  work=Spokane Spokesman-Review  date=2004-06-06  accessdate=2014-01-20  page=C5
As the 200405 NHL season went unplayed due to a 200405 NHL lockout labour dispute, Glinas spent the season in Switzerland.cite news  url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D94885SO4.html  title=NHL veteran Martin Gelinas joins Swiss club  publisher=Associated Press  date=2008-11-04  accessdate=2014-01-20subscription required via=Highbeam He played one regular season and five playoff games with HC Lugano in the National League A Nationalliga A NLA, but otherwise spent the season with HC Forward-Morges in the National League B Nationalliga B NLB where he scored 37 goals in 41 games and recorded 58 points. A free agent when the NHL resumed play in 200506 NHL season 200506, Glinas signed a two-year contract with the Florida Panthers.cite news  url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/apnews/stories/080205/D8BO1SAG0.shtml  title=Panthers sign veteran Gelinas, re-sign two minor leaguers  work=Florida Times-Union  date=2005-08-02  accessdate=2014-01-20 Brought in as a capable veteran, he played all 82 games for Florida and scored over 40 points in each season. Glinas scored his 300th career goal in Florida's final game of the 200607 NHL season 200607 season.cite news  url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=270407007  title=Brind'Amour, Canes beat Panthers with last-minute score  publisher=ESPN  date=2007-04-07  accessdate=2014-01-20
Leaving Florida, Glinas signed with the Nashville Predators for the 200708 NHL season 200708 season.cite news  url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=20070727&id=MAAsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cm0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=5293,2433069  title=Predators sign Gelinas  work=Kentucky New Era  date=2007-07-27  accessdate=2014-01-20  page=B3 He had 20 points in 57 games before suffering a anterior cruciate ligament injury torn anterior cruciate ligament in February 21, 2008, game against the Vancouver Canucks that was ultimately his final contest in the NHL.cite web  url=http://m.espn.go.com/nhl/playerupdate?playerId=301&wjb=  title=Martin Gelinas status updates  publisher=ESPN  accessdate=2014-01-20 Glinas returned to Switzerland 200809 as he signed a contract to play with SC Bern in the NLA. In 27 games, he scored 15 goals and 22 points. He retired following the season.  In his NHL career, Glinas played 1,273 regular season games and added 147 in the playoffs.cite news  last=Pap  first=Elliott  url=http://www2.canada.com/story.html?id=7862599  title=Ex-Canuck Marty Gelinas makes coaching debut with Flames  work=Vancouver Sun  date=2013-01-23  accessdate=2014-01-23 His former junior team, now known as the Gatineau Olympiques, retired his uniform number 20 in 2012.cite web  url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=646200  title=Martin Gelinas' jersey to be retired by the Gatineau Olympiques  publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club  date=2012-11-22  accessdate=2014-01-23
Coaching career
The Nashville Predators hired Glinas as their director of player development in 2009. He had spent the final years of his playing career mentoring younger teammates and general Manager David Poile praised him as being an ideal person for the role: we will depend on Martin and his experience, work ethic and professionalism to help develop our prospects into NHL players.cite news  url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/nhlnews/story.html?id=4215aba4-5f34-4d06-a1dc-7f3e72a85a01  title=Gelinas named Preds' player development chief  publisher=Canwest News Service  date=2009-06-16  accessdate=2014-01-23 Spending up to 20 days per month on the road, he often served in a coaching capacity by assisting players during practices when visiting Nashville's farm club, the Milwaukee Admirals. He carried that experience back to Calgary in 2012 when he was hired as the Flames' assistant coach under Bob Hartley. One of Glinas duties with the team is to work with the special teams units, both the power play sporting term power play and the Short-handed penalty kill.cite news  url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/martin-gelinas-joins-flames-coaching-staff-1.1198386  title=Martin Gelinas joins Flames coaching staff  publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation  date=2012-06-14  accessdate=2014-01-23 The 201314 NHL season 201314 season is his second with the team.cite book  editor-last=Hanlon  editor-first=Peter  editor-last2=Kelso  editor-first2=Sean  editor-last3=Thomas  editor-first3=Rob  title=201314 Calgary Flames Media Guide  publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club  year=2013  page=14
Personal life
A native of Shawinigan-Sud, Quebec, Martin is the son of Ren Glinas and Lise Lebel.cite news  title=Une famille en peine: les Glinas y ont cru jusqu'au bout  work=Le Soleil  location=Quebec City, QC  date=2004-06-08  page=S2  language=French His father was a barber in Shawinigan-Sud.cite news  last=Spector  first=Mark  title=Highs and lows: After a career like his, no one knows better than Martin Gelinas that anything is possible in both life and the pursuit of the Stanley Cup  work=National Post  date=2004-04-08  page=S5 Martin and his wife Jane have three children: son Matthew and daughters Cameron and Morgan.  The family have made Calgary their permanent home since he first signed with the Flames in 2002. Mathew is also a hockey player, and in 201314 is in junior as a member of the Tri-City Americans.cite news  url=http://amshockey.com/article/americans-sign-prospect-matthew-gelinas/135599  title=Americans sign prospect Matthew Gelinas  publisher=Tri-City Americans Hockey Club  date=2013-01-08  accessdate=2014-01-23
Active with charitable endeavours throughout his career, Glinas was named the recipient of the List of Calgary Flames award winners#Ralph T. Scurfield Humanitarian Award Ralph T. Scurfield Humanitarian Award in 2004.  A Calgary Flames team award, it is given to the player who best combines on-ice leadership with a dedication to community service. He is involved with the Calgary Flames Alumni Association's charitable events.cite web  last=Rodger  first=Andrew  url=http://www.nhlalumni.net/news/19th-annual-calgary-flames-alumni-golf-tournament  title=The 19th Annual Calgary Flames Alumni Golf Tournament  publisher=National Hockey League Alumni Association  accessdate=2014-01-23 Glinas is also involved with Calgary's business industry: He holds an interest in Calgary-based Whitecap Resources.cite web  last=Angerman  first=Liane  url=http://www.theogm.com/2013/04/04/martin-gelinas-a-new-chapter-in-oil-and-gas-leadership/  title=Martin Gelinas: A New Chapter in Oil and Gas Leadership  work=The OGM  date=2013-04-04  accessdate=2014-01-23
